    <title>Combined summary - User Activated Soft Fork Split Protection</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T02:06:55.705770+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-June/014535.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers have proposed the "splitprotection" Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) to reduce the risk of a potential chain split during the activation of BIP148, a user-activated soft fork (UASF) to implement SegWit on the Bitcoin network. The proposal enables miners to activate SegWit mandatory signaling and prevent a potential chain split ahead of the August 1st BIP148 activation date by signaling for split protection. To prevent a potential chain split ahead of the BIP148 activation, James Hilliard proposed the "splitprotection" soft fork. This proposal allows miners to activate existing segwit deployment using less than 95% hashpower before BIP148 activation. It reduces the chance of an extended chain split by using a simple miner majority of 65% over a 504 block interval. All blocks must set the nVersion header top 3 bits to 001 together with bit field (1&gt; existing SegWit deployment). Blocks that do not signal as required will be rejected. Users are advised to upgrade their nodes to support split protection or wait for additional confirmations when accepting payments while this bip is active. The proposal is designed to ensure that there is no chain split during the upcoming BIP148 activation.The proposal uses a BIP8 style timeout to ensure compatibility with BIP148, and BIP148-compatible mandatory signaling activates regardless of miner signaling levels. While there is growing support for BIP148, it may not have enough economic backing or hashpower initially, which could result in a lag time after the split. In response to market forces, the proposal allows miners to signal their intention to run BIP148 and prevent a chain split. The split protection deployment is compatible with the existing "segwit" bit 1 deployment scheduled between midnight November 15th, 2016, and midnight November 15th, 2017. To ensure compatibility with BIP148, a BIP8 style timeout has been proposed.The context also includes information about the SegWit2x agreement, which proposes a new option for miners to prevent a chain split ahead of the August 1 BIP148 activation date. The proposed solution is called splitprotection soft fork and is essentially BIP91 but with a lower activation threshold and immediate mandatory signalling lock-in, using BIP8 instead of BIP9. Splitprotection allows for a majority of miners to activate mandatory SegWit signalling and prevent a potential chain split ahead of BIP148 activation.However, there are concerns that the proposal may be rushed and force miners to upgrade quickly or get orphaned. Jared Lee Richardson raised concerns about the psychology of giving BIP148 a sense of safety that may not be valid. The need for strong economic support and profitability for miners is highlighted as a key factor in ensuring the safety and stability of Bitcoin. While differing opinions exist, all parties agree on the importance of finding a solution that avoids a prolonged chain split.The document includes references related to Bitcoin development and is dual-licensed as BSD 3-clause and Creative Commons CC0 1.0 Universal. A mailing list post regarding SegWit was also provided in the context, which provides information on the benefits of SegWit and mentions that the document is dual licensed under BSD 3-clause and Creative Commons CC0 1.0 Universal. Overall, the splitprotection BIP provides a coordination mechanism for a simple majority of miners to prevent a chain split ahead of BIP148 activation. It leverages `IsSuperMajority()` to activate soft forks in a backwards compatible way. While differing opinions exist, all parties agree on the importance of finding a solution that avoids a prolonged chain split.</summary>
